        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <p>
              The 1960s Caribbean and Central America were alive with independence struggles, revolutions, and U.S. intervention. Jamaica gained independence in 1962, Cuba was navigating post-revolution life under Castro, while Puerto Rico grappled with identity as a U.S. territory. In places like Haiti and the Dominican Republic, political unrest and dictatorships coexisted with vibrant music scenes. These shifts directly influenced the music — protest themes, diasporic pride, and celebration of local identity were everywhere.            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- What People Were Hearing -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/10 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 19V6l12-3v13M9 19c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zm12-3c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zM9 10l12-3"></path>
            </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">What People Were Hearing</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            Before the rock ’n’ roll invasion fully swept in, much of the Caribbean was already rhythmically rich and extremely Dance influenced. <br/>
          <!-- Subsections -->
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
         <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Jamaica:</span> Mento and ska, with jazz-influenced horn sections and syncopated rhythms. Ska would evolve into rocksteady later in the decade.
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Cuba:</span> Son Cubano, mambo, and cha-cha-cha were staples, but after the revolution many artists migrated (like Celia Cruz), spreading Cuban sound worldwide.
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center my-2 space-x-2">
              <img src="https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/carri_assets/content_images/Son_band_Occidente.jpeg" alt="Son Band Occidente" class="w-64 h-64 rounded-xl object-cover">
              <span class="text-sm text-[#064161]/80">Son Band Occidente </span> <br/>
              
          </div>  
        </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Trinidad & Tobago:</span> Calypso reigned supreme, with witty social commentary baked into playful lyrics.
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Haiti:</span> Méringue  and compas direct (a modernization of méringue by Nemours Jean-Baptiste) took center stage.
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center my-2 space-x-2">
              <img src="https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/carri_assets/content_images/Jaime_Colson_Merengue.jpg" alt="Meringue band" class="w-64 h-64 rounded-xl object-cover">
              <span class="text-sm text-[#064161]/80">Meringue band </span> <br/>
              
          </div>  
        </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
          <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Central America:</span> Panama and Costa Rica absorbed calypso and mento via migrant communities, while Nicaragua and Guatemala leaned into marimba-based folk traditions.
                    </div>

          <p>
            Fun bit: while Europe was swooning over Beatles harmonies, Caribbean kids were more likely to be dancing to ska 45s pressed in Kingston’s tiny studios.

          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      </div>

      <!-- What you can find in this playlist -->
