            </div>  
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Cuba:</span> Well-funded big bands with horn sections and percussion-heavy lineups dominated recording halls until the exodus of musicians post-revolution.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Haiti:</span> Electric guitar started creeping into compas, modernizing folk dance sounds.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Trinidad:</span> The steelpan (born in the 1940s from oil drums) became central to both street bands and competitions, evolving its tonal range through the ’60s.
            <div class="flex flex-col items-center my-2 space-x-2">
              <img src="https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/carri_assets/content_images/Steelpan.jpeg" alt="Steelpan" class="w-64 h-64 rounded-xl object-cover">
              <span class="text-sm text-[#064161]/80">Steelpan </span> <br/>
            </div>  
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold text-[#064161]">Central America:</span> Marimba orchestras in Guatemala and Nicaragua were electrified, blending folk tradition with popular dance music.
            </div>

            </div>  
            
          
        </div>
